{
    "analysis": "None",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv from the current directory. For each file, compute and return a compact summary (limit lists to top 20 elements): 1) total row count, 2) min and max timestamp, 3) the top up-to-20 unique cmdb_id values, 4) the top up-to-20 unique KPI/trace/log names (kpi_name for metric.csv, trace_name for trace.csv, log_name for log.csv; for error_logs.csv list 'message' sample), and 5) show up to the first 5 rows of the file. Return results as plain text / small tables. Keep outputs bounded and concise." 
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous step loaded all four telemetry files and produced compact summaries. Key observations: metric.csv and trace.csv cover the full window 2022-03-21 01:30:00–01:59:00 (UTC+8). error_logs.csv contains 543 warning messages all like \"failed to retrieve ads\" concentrated on frontend-* components (frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2) very early in the window (timestamps starting at 2022-03-21 01:30:04 UTC+8). This suggests at least one failure involves frontend components and ad retrieval. We still need systematic metric-based anomaly detection (global thresholds per component-KPI) to find faults and exact occurrence times for the two failures in the interval. No metric-level thresholds have been computed yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, aggregate time series by (cmdb_id, kpi_name) across the full available data (do NOT filter to the incident window yet). For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: count, min_timestamp, max_timestamp, mean, min, max, 95th percentile (P95), and 5th percentile (P5). Store the full aggregation table in a kernel variable for later use. Return a compact table showing the top 20 rows ordered by count (highest first) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count, min_timestamp, max_timestamp, mean, min, max, P95, P5. Limit the returned rows to those top 20 only."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have aggregated metric.csv into metric_agg_df and computed global statistics (count, min/max timestamps, mean, min, max, P95, P5) for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) group across the full available data (not filtered). Observations so far: many container/node-level network and memory KPIs exist (e.g., container.node-5.*) and error_logs point to frontend-* reporting \"failed to retrieve ads\" very early in the window (around 2022-03-21 01:30:04 UTC+8). Next, we must detect metric anomalies inside the incident window (2022-03-21 01:30:00 to 2022-03-21 02:00:00 UTC+8) by comparing per-group values in that window to the previously computed global thresholds (P95 and P5). This will help narrow candidate faulty components and exact fault start times. No per-window anomaly scan has been run yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv and the previously stored metric_agg_df (global stats per group), filter metric.csv to the incident window: timestamps from 2022-03-21 01:30:00 (inclusive) to 2022-03-21 02:00:00 (exclusive) in UTC+8. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) group present in metric_agg_df, compute within-window aggregates: count_in_window, min_in_window, max_in_window, timestamp_of_min (earliest if multiple), timestamp_of_max (earliest if multiple). Join these with the group's global P95 and P5 from metric_agg_df and compute two severity scores: upward_breach_ratio = (max_in_window - P95)/P95 (set to 0 if P95==0 or max_in_window<=P95) and downward_breach_ratio = (P5 - min_in_window)/P5 (set to 0 if P5==0 or min_in_window>=P5). Return a compact table of the top 20 groups sorted by max(upward_breach_ratio, downward_breach_ratio) descending, with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count_in_window, min_in_window, timestamp_of_min, max_in_window, timestamp_of_max, global_P95, global_P5, upward_breach_ratio, downward_breach_ratio. Limit returned rows to 20."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous metric-level aggregation and window-joined breach scoring, the dominant anomalies are large coordinated upward spikes in container.node-5.container_network_receive_MB.* across many services, plus node-level spikes: node-1 system.net.tcp.retrans_segs and node-4 system.io.w_s. This pattern suggests a network throughput/congestion issue on node-5 (affecting many containers colocated on that node) and additional node-level resource spikes that may represent two separate incidents or related symptoms. To localize the two failures and determine exact occurrence times, we need the earliest breach timestamps (first timepoint in the incident window where metric > global P95) for the top candidate KPIs (the node-5 container network MB metrics across services and the node-level retransmission and disk-write KPIs). Identifying the earliest breach times and clustering them will let us separate the two failure events and then use traces/logs to confirm downstream faulty components (e.g., frontends) and reasons (e.g., network packet retransmission/congestion).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric_agg_df and metric_window_agg_df: select groups where upward_breach_ratio > 1 and (kpi_name contains 'container_network_receive_MB' OR kpi_name == 'system.net.tcp.retrans_segs' OR kpi_name == 'system.io.w_s'). Using metric.csv filtered to the incident window (2022-03-21 01:30:00 to 2022-03-21 02:00:00 UTC+8), for each selected (cmdb_id, kpi_name) find the earliest timestamp where value > that group's global P95 and the value at that timestamp. Return a compact table (limit 30 rows) ordered by earliest breach timestamp ascending with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, earliest_breach_timestamp (UTC+8), value_at_earliest, global_P95, upward_breach_ratio. Store the detailed results in kernel variable: earliest_breaches_df."
}

{
    "analysis": "Executor produced earliest_breaches_df listing 22 groups whose values exceeded their global P95 during the incident window. Key deductions: (1) a coordinated set of container-level network receive MB spikes (container.node-5.container_network_receive_MB.*) began as early as 2022-03-21 01:30:00 (UTC+8) for multiple services, indicating a widespread network throughput/congestion event affecting containers on node-5 (one container on node-6 also shows high receive). (2) Node-level anomalies are present: system.net.tcp.retrans_segs breaches (node-4 at 01:31 and node-1 later at 01:48) indicating packet retransmission spikes, and a node-4 system.io.w_s (disk write/sec) spike at 01:56. (3) error_logs earlier showed frontend-* warnings (“failed to retrieve ads”) concentrated near 01:30:04, consistent with the network event at 01:30. These patterns suggest at least one failure starting at ~01:30 tied to network congestion/retransmission on node-5 (impacting many services and frontends). There is also a later strong node-level disk-write spike at ~01:56 which may correspond to a second failure; alternatively, the later node-1 retransmission at 01:48 could be another failure. To decide the two failures precisely we must identify fault intervals (consecutive minutes above threshold) and their start times and severities for the candidate groups (the 22 breached groups). From those faults we can then use traces/logs to confirm affected downstream services and root cause reason. Next step: identify fault intervals for each candidate group (start, end, duration, peak and severity).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv filtered to incident window (2022-03-21 01:30:00 to 2022-03-21 02:00:00 UTC+8) and the global P95 from metric_agg_df, for each of the 22 groups listed in earliest_breaches_df: scan the group's per-minute series and identify consecutive intervals where value > global_P95. For each interval produce one row with: cmdb_id, kpi_name, interval_start_timestamp (UTC+8), interval_end_timestamp (UTC+8, inclusive), duration_minutes, max_value_in_interval, timestamp_of_max_in_interval (UTC+8), global_P95, severity_ratio = max_value_in_interval / global_P95. Store result as kernel variable faults_df. Return a compact table of all fault intervals (limit to top 30 rows) ordered by interval_start_timestamp ascending." 
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocessing and metric-based anomaly detection: global P95/P5 thresholds were computed per (cmdb_id, kpi_name); metric-window analysis found 22 groups with strong upward breaches. The dominant signal is coordinated, large spikes in container.node-5.container_network_receive_MB.* across many services beginning as early as 2022-03-21 01:30:00 (UTC+8). Node-level anomalies include system.net.tcp.retrans_segs (breaches at 01:31 and later at 01:48) and system.io.w_s (disk write spike at 01:56). error_logs.csv earlier showed many frontend-* warnings (“failed to retrieve ads”) starting at 01:30:04, which aligns with the early network receive spikes on node-5. We need to localize the two distinct failures within 01:30–02:00: one appears to start at ~01:30 (network congestion impacting frontends and many services on node-5), and another candidate event occurs later (node-level retransmission at 01:48 or disk write spike at 01:56). To confirm the failures and assign exact root-cause components/times/reasons, we must use traces and logs to (a) find the earliest user-facing errors or trace error_rate/latency increases that coincide with metric faults, and (b) see whether a second distinct incident correlates with the node-1/node-4 spikes or is part of a sustained event. At this point we do NOT yet have the trace/log correlation for the second failure and need targeted inspection of error_logs, trace error_rate and duration metrics around the candidate timestamps.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Analyze error_logs.csv within the incident window (2022-03-21 01:30:00 to 2022-03-21 02:00:00 UTC+8). Provide a compact summary with: 1) per-minute total error_log counts (sorted by timestamp ascending) for the window; 2) top cmdb_id by total error_log count (top 10) with their earliest and latest error timestamps; 3) the earliest 20 error_log rows (timestamp, cmdb_id, message) ordered by timestamp ascending. Return results bounded and concise. Store the per-minute aggregation and top-cmdb_id table in kernel variables error_logs_per_min_df and error_logs_top_cmdb_df for later use."
}

{
    "analysis": "trace.csv has been aggregated into trace_agg_df (global thresholds P95/P5 computed per (cmdb_id, trace_name) across the full data). Top trace groups are the usual front-end to service traces (trace.from_frontend-*.duration_mean/p95/error_rate/row_count) with stable, low latencies and mostly zero error_rate in their historical data. What remains is to use these trace thresholds to detect anomalies within the incident window and to localize the most-downstream faulty service/container for each failure. Specifically, we need to check trace error_rate (upward anomalies), trace duration_p95 (upward latency spikes), and trace row_count (downward drops) within 2022-03-21 01:30:00–02:00:00 (UTC+8) and find earliest breach timestamps per trace group. Those earliest trace anomalies, correlated with metric faults (node-5 network spikes) and frontend error logs, will let us identify the root-cause component(s) and exact occurrence times for the two failures (the early ~01:30 event and the later event around 01:48–01:56).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace_agg_df (global P95 and P5 already computed) and raw trace.csv filtered to incident window 2022-03-21 01:30:00–02:00:00 UTC+8, examine trace groups where trace_name contains 'error_rate' or 'duration_p95' or 'row_count'. For each group: determine whether an anomaly occurred in-window by these rules: (a) for 'error_rate' and 'duration_p95', anomaly = value > global P95; (b) for 'row_count', anomaly = value < global P5. For each group that has at least one anomaly, find the earliest anomaly timestamp and the value at that timestamp. Produce a compact table (limit 20 rows) ordered by earliest anomaly timestamp ascending with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_type ('up' for error_rate/duration_p95, 'down' for row_count), global_P95 (or global_P5 for row_count), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC+8), value_at_earliest, and severity_ratio (value/global_P95 for 'up' anomalies, global_P5/value for 'down' anomalies). Store full results in kernel variable trace_earliest_anoms_df and return the compact table."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed global threshold calculation for metrics and traces, windowed metric anomaly detection, fault-interval extraction for the top breached groups, and trace anomaly detection within the incident window. What we know so far: \n- A widespread, high-severity set of container-level network receive MB spikes (container.node-5.container_network_receive_MB.*) began at 2022-03-21 01:30:00 (UTC+8) affecting many services. These are accompanied by frontend error logs (\"failed to retrieve ads\") starting at ~01:30:04 UTC+8 and by trace anomalies (increased duration_p95 / decreased row_count) beginning at ~01:30. Node-level TCP retransmission spikes (system.net.tcp.retrans_segs) were observed (one at 01:31 and another at 01:48 UTC+8). A node-4 disk write I/O spike (system.io.w_s) occurred at 01:56 UTC+8.\n- From the rules: when many containers on the same node show coordinated faults, the node is the likely root cause; when multiple components of the same level are faulty, use traces/logs to pick the most downstream faulty component. Right now the first failure is strongly indicated as a node-level network issue on node-5 starting at 2022-03-21 01:30:00 UTC+8. \n- However, the task states there were two failures in the 01:30–02:00 window. We must confirm whether the later node-level anomalies (node-1 retrans at 01:48 or node-4 disk write at 01:56) correspond to a second distinct failure (with its own root cause component/time/reason) or are part of the sustained initial incident. To decide, we need to correlate timings: count of metric fault interval starts per minute, count of trace anomaly starts per minute, and error_log counts per minute across the window to see distinct temporal clusters (one around 01:30 and another later). This will let us map a second failure to the appropriate node or set of components.\n",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Produce a per-minute correlation table for the incident window (2022-03-21 01:30:00 to 2022-03-21 01:59:00 UTC+8) with three columns: timestamp (minute, UTC+8), metric_fault_starts (count of fault intervals in faults_df whose interval_start_ts equals that minute), trace_anom_starts (count of trace groups in trace_earliest_anoms_df whose earliest_anomaly_timestamp equals that minute), and error_log_count (count from error_logs_per_min_df for that minute). Use the kernel variables faults_df, trace_earliest_anoms_df, and error_logs_per_min_df. Return the full per-minute table for the 30 minutes (limit 30 rows), ordered by timestamp ascending. Store the result in kernel variable per_min_correlation_df." 
}

{
    "analysis": "We built a per-minute correlation table (per_min_correlation_df) that shows a strong, immediate cluster of trace anomalies and frontend error logs starting at 2022-03-21 01:30:00 (UTC+8). Metric-detected fault intervals are distributed across the window but include an early start at 01:30 and a later concentrated spike at 01:56 (and a notable node-level retransmission event at 01:48). From earlier steps we know: (a) many containers on node-5 show coordinated, high-severity container_network_receive_MB spikes beginning at 01:30:00; (b) frontend pods log repeated \"failed to retrieve ads\" warnings beginning ~01:30:04; (c) many trace groups show early anomalies (increased p95/drops) at ~01:30; (d) node-level tcp retransmit and disk-write spikes occur later (01:31, 01:48, 01:56). These data strongly indicate the first failure began at ~01:30 and is a node-level network throughput/congestion issue (node-5) that impacted many services and frontends. The evidence for a second distinct failure is less certain: candidates are the 01:48 node-1 tcp retransmit spike or the 01:56 node-4 disk write I/O spike, both accompanied by metric fault-start counts peaking later. To determine the exact root-cause component/time/reason for each of the two failures we must inspect which faults (component-KPI intervals) actually start at the candidate minutes and their severities. Identifying the dominant faulty component(s) and their first anomalous minute will let us apply the root-cause rules (choose node-level for coordinated container faults; use traces/logs if multiple same-level components are faulty).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From faults_df (the extracted fault intervals), filter for intervals whose interval_start_timestamp is one of: 2022-03-21 01:30:00 CST, 2022-03-21 01:48:00 CST, and 2022-03-21 01:56:00 CST (UTC+8). For each of those three minutes produce a compact table (limit top 20 rows per minute) sorted by severity_ratio descending with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, interval_start_timestamp, interval_end_timestamp, duration_minutes, max_value_in_interval, timestamp_of_max_in_interval, global_P95, severity_ratio. Store the three resulting tables in kernel variables faults_01_30_df, faults_01_48_df, faults_01_56_df and return them. Keep outputs bounded to at most 20 rows per minute." 
}

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the full workflow up to fault identification and trace/log correlation. What has been done: global thresholds were computed for metrics and traces; metric anomalies in the incident window were detected and fault intervals extracted (faults_df). Trace anomalies were detected and earliest occurrences recorded (trace_earliest_anoms_df). Error logs were aggregated per minute and show frontend warnings starting at ~01:30:04 UTC+8. Per-minute correlation (per_min_correlation_df) shows a dominant, immediate incident at 01:30 (many trace anomalies and frontend error logs) plus later metric fault-start spikes, notably at 01:56 (metric_fault_starts peak=5) and a strong node-level tcp retransmission event at 01:48 and disk write I/O spike at 01:56. From metric-level rules, the coordinated container-level container_network_receive_MB spikes across many services indicate a node-level network issue (node-5) beginning at 2022-03-21 01:30:00 UTC+8 — this aligns with frontend error logs and trace anomalies at 01:30, so Failure #1 is strongly indicated as node-5 network congestion starting at 01:30:00 UTC+8. The need now is to determine the second distinct failure: candidates are the node-1 system.net.tcp.retrans_segs spike at 01:48:00 UTC+8 and the node-4 system.io.w_s (disk write I/O) spike at 01:56:00 UTC+8, both with high severity. To decide which corresponds to the second failure (or whether both are separate failures), we must correlate per-minute evidence for those minutes: counts and top affected components from faults_df, presence of node-level KPIs, trace anomaly starts, and error_log counts. This will let us apply the root-cause rules (node-level vs container-level and most significant deviation) and finalize the two failures' root cause components, exact occurrence datetimes, and reasons.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For the two candidate minutes 2022-03-21 01:48:00 CST and 2022-03-21 01:56:00 CST (UTC+8), produce a compact summary (one row per minute) with these fields: minute_timestamp, metric_fault_starts_count (count of fault intervals in faults_df starting at that minute), top_cmdb_ids (top up to 10 cmdb_id by number of faults starting at that minute, with counts), node_level_kpis_present (True/False and list of any cmdb_id equal to 'node-*' appearing among faults starting that minute), trace_anom_starts_count (count of trace groups in trace_earliest_anoms_df whose earliest_anomaly_timestamp equals that minute), and error_log_count (from error_logs_per_min_df for that minute). Limit returned output to these two rows and keep it concise." 
}

